## Migration: `TimedExecutor` to .NET 8

### Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Never thrown — dead code |

`Thread.Abort` was removed because it corrupts application state by unwinding the stack at arbitrary points, potentially leaving locks held and data structures half-written.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The delegate must observe the <see cref="CancellationToken"/> to stop promptly.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller until completion or timeout.
            // Task.Wait throws AggregateException on faults or cancellation.
            task.Wait(CancellationToken.None);
            return task.Result;
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerException is OperationCanceledException)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout", ex.InnerException);
        }
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Async-native overload — preferred in async call chains.
    /// </summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Usage

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// Synchronous — the lambda MUST check the token
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // cooperative exit point
        // ... do work ...
    }
    return 42;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// Async
var data = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(async ct =>
{
    return await httpClient.GetStringAsync(url, ct);
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10));
```

### Critical Pitfalls

**1. Cooperative cancellation is not automatic.** Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, the token doesn't force termination. If the delegate ignores the token, it runs to completion despite the timeout. CPU-bound loops **must** poll `ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()`.

**2. Uncooperative work requires a fire-and-forget wrapper.** If you call third-party code that can't accept a token:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeoutUncooperative<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    // The task may keep running after timeout — we just stop waiting.
    var task = Task.Run(work);

    if (task.Wait(timeout))
        return task.Result;

    // Task is abandoned — it will eventually complete or fault silently.
    // This is the best you can do without Thread.Abort.
    throw new TimeoutException(
        $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout (task abandoned)");
}
```

> ⚠️ The abandoned task leaks its thread until completion. This is intentional — it's still safer than `Thread.Abort()` corrupting shared state.

**3. Signature change is breaking.** The delegate changed from `Func<T>` to `Func<CancellationToken, T>`. Callers must be updated.

**4. `Task.Wait()` wraps exceptions.** .NET Framework's version threw a bare `AggregateException(innerEx)`. The new version may double-wrap if you're not careful — the `when` clause above handles this correctly.

**5. `WaitAsync` is .NET 6+.** The async overload uses `Task.WaitAsync(CancellationToken)` which doesn't exist in older targets. This is fine for .NET 8.
